        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Now I have a clear picture. Here's my analysis:\n\n---\n\n## Root Cause Analysis — Issue #66\n\n**The bug**: Both `HttpTransport::fetch_once()` (`http.rs:421`) and `TransportPool::fetch_from_targets()` (`pool.rs:648`) aggregate multi-node responses into a `HashMap<MessageID, OuterEnvelope>` using a plain `.insert()`. Since `HashMap::insert` overwrites existing values, the **last relay processed wins** — with no comparison, no conflict detection, and no logging.\n\n**Why it's dangerous**: The threat model (WHITEPAPER.md) explicitly includes compromised relays and active injection. A malicious relay can return a tampered envelope with the same `message_id` (a UUIDv4), and the aggregation silently replaces the legitimate copy. Since `OuterEnvelope` doesn't derive `PartialEq`, there's currently no cheap way to even compare two envelopes. Combined with destructive fetch (node deletes after serving), the valid copy is permanently lost.\n\n**Key structural details**:\n- `MessageID` is a UUID v4 wrapper — collision between honest senders is astronomically unlikely, so any collision across relays means either a legitimate replica or a tampered copy\n- `OuterEnvelope` has no `PartialEq`, no `Hash` (on the full struct), and no serialized-bytes accessor — comparing two envelopes currently requires manual field comparison or re-serialization\n- The same copy-paste dedup pattern exists in two places (http.rs and pool.rs)\n\n---\n\n## Proposed Fixes (from simplest to most robust)\n\n### Option A: First-write-wins + conflict logging (minimal, low risk)\n\nChange `.insert()` to `.entry().or_insert()` so the **first** copy seen is kept. Log a warning when a duplicate `message_id` arrives with different bytes.\n\n```rust\nuse std::collections::hash_map::Entry;\n\nfor msg in messages {\n    match messages_by_id.entry(msg.message_id) {\n        Entry::Vacant(e) => { e.insert(msg); }\n        Entry::Occupied(existing) => {\n            // Compare serialized bytes to de